ons of Tocqueville’s work, and this fresh look at his writings provides a powerful framework for addressing the tensions between liberalism and democracy in the twenty-first century.Recovering a richer liberalism capable of weathering today’s political storms, Tocqueville’s Dilemmas, and Ours explains how we can reclaim nationalism as a liberal force and reimagine sovereignty in a global age—and do so with one of democracy’s most discerning thinkers as our guide.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDemocracy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aA Different Story.  aAccountability.  aAdvocacy.  aAlexis de Tocqueville.  aAlgeria.  aAmbiguity.  aAryeh Neier.  aAttempt.  aAuthoritarianism.  aCentrality.  aChauvinism.  aCollective identity.  aCompetition.  aConsideration.  aContexts.  aCost.  aDavid Webber.  aDebate.  aDecision-making.  aDeclamation.  aDeliberation.  aDisadvantage.  aEastern Question.  aEmployment.  aEntrapment.  aEnumerated powers.  aEthos.  aExecutive director.  aFareed Zakaria.  aFeeling.  aForeign policy.  aFrank Kameny.  aGenre.  aGeorge Chauncey.  aGlobalization.  aGovernance.  aIdeology.  aImplementation.  aIndividual.  aInsignificance.  aInstitution.  aIntellectual.  aInternational crisis.  aInternational relations.  aIrony.  aJohn Marshall.  aJohn-Manuel Andriote.  aKelly Services.  aKompetenz-kompetenz.  aLee Badgett.  aLesbian.  aLiberal democracy.  aManagement.  aMartin Duberman.  aMessianism.  aMontesquieu.  aNation.  aNationalism.  aNullification Crisis.  aObstacle.  aOppression.  aOwnership.  aPatriotism.  aPeculiar institution.  aPersuasion.  aPhenomenon.  aPlaintiff.  aPolicy.  aPolitical consciousness.  aPolitics.  aPrecedent.  aPrerogative.  aPubl